            <h1>Public unions protect communities</h1>
            <p class="usa-intro">Support contracts that build bonds; reject those that collect them.</p>
            <h2>Rebuild trust and accountability</h2>
            <p>Police unions often have contracts with the communities they are supposed to protect and serve. Usually, it is only politicians and police unions (e.g., Fraternal Order of Police) that are involved in coming up with these terms. These terms include when force can be used, how discipline and promotions work, as well as how compensation - for the officers and plaintiffs in lawsuits - is paid from your taxes.</p>
            <p>Integrating the community and the police by making sure each works for and with the other is an important first step towards real, lasting, reform. Review your each and every police contract that covers where you live and work. If you don't see yours, follow our <a href="resources/#steps-for-success" alt="">steps for success</a>, and if you find a contract, <a href="https://github.com/LocalOPC/LocalOPC.org" alt="A link to the GitHub repository for this website." target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">share it with us</a> so we can put it on this website!</p>
            <p>Once you know when your community's police force's contract expires, find out the next hearing associated with the renegotiation and attend with your neighbors and friends. Make sure your elected officials hear what matters most to you.</p>
            
            <!-- Upcoming renewals -->
