            <!-- Why this matters -->
            <h2 id="why-this-matters">Why should this matter to you?</h2>
            <p>
              In 2016, the <a href="http://useofforceproject.org/" alt="The official webpage for the Use of Force Project." target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Use of Force Project</a> reviewed use of force policies in the 100 largest American cities. <a href="https://static1.squarespace.com/static/56996151cbced68b170389f4/t/57e1b5cc2994ca4ac1d97700/1474409936835/Police+Use+of+Force+Report.pdf" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Only 9 out of those 100 police forces didn't kill someone in 2015 or 2016</a> <img src="<?php echo $path;?>assets/images/pdf.png" alt="Icon of a PDF file created by Freepik on Flaticon.com." class="icon-pdf" />. The review consisted of eight major policies that were identified as establishing a meaningful restriction on police use of force. They are:
              <ol>
                <li>Require officers to de-escalate situations</li>
                <li>Use a force continuum or matrix</li>
                <li>Restrict chokeholds and strangleholds</li>
                <li>Require officers to give a verbal warning</li>
                <li>Prohibit officers from shooting at people in moving vehicles</li>
                <li>Require officers to exhaust all other reasonable alternatives</li>
                <li>Require officers to intervene</li>
                <li>Require comprehensive reporting</li>
              </ol>
            </p>
            <p>There isn't a single police department in the entire country that has implemented all eight.</p>
            <p>Also in 2016, the <a href="https://www.checkthepolice.org/" alt="The official webpage for the Police Union Contract Project." target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Police Union Contract Project</a> reviewed police union contracts in 81 of the 100 largest American cities (3 refused to send their contracts and the other 16 do not have contracts). <a href="https://static1.squarespace.com/static/559fbf2be4b08ef197467542/t/5773f695f7e0abbdfe28a1f0/1467217560243/Campaign+Zero+Police+Union+Contract+Report.pdf" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">72 of the 81 have at least one barrier to police accountability</a> <img src="<?php echo $path;?>assets/images/pdf.png" alt="Icon of a PDF file created by Freepik on Flaticon.com." class="icon-pdf" />. The review consisted of six major area that were identified as establishing one of those barriers. They are:
              <ol>
                <li><strong>Disqualifying misconduct complaints</strong> that are submitted too many days after an incident occurs or if an investigation takes too long to complete.</li>
                <li><strong>Preventing police officers from being interrogated immediately</strong> after being involved in an incident or otherwise restricting how, when, or where they can be interrogated.</li>
                <li><strong>Giving officers access to information that civilians do not get</strong> prior to being interrogated.</li>
                <li><strong>Requiring cities to pay costs related to police misconduct</strong> including by giving officers paid leave while under investigation, paying legal fees, and/or the cost of settlements.</li>
                <li><strong>Preventing information on past misconduct</strong> investigations from being recorded or retained in an officer's personnel file.</li>
                <li><strong>Limiting disciplinary consequences</strong> for officers or limiting the capacity of civilian oversight structures and/or the media to hold police accountable.</li>
              </ol>
            </p>
            <p>Only 15 states have a police bill of rights. If your state isn't one of them, work to change that.</p>
